There is a long-standing observation behind what you’re pointing to: people in conflicts often act as though legitimacy will be judged retrospectively. If they believe they’ll prevail, they may assume future narratives will emphasize their achievements, minimize their mistakes, or reinterpret controversial actions.

The phrase “history is written by the victors” captures part of this intuition, though historians often point out it’s only partly true. In the short term, winners usually have more power over institutions, archives, education, and public messaging. Over longer periods, however, narratives are often revised as new documents emerge, former opponents publish accounts, and later generations reassess events. Many once-celebrated leaders have later been criticized, and some defeated groups have later received more sympathetic treatment.

Your reference to President Trump’s relationship with the media reflects another aspect of this dynamic: competing groups are often engaged in a struggle over narrative while events are still unfolding. Different outlets, politicians, commentators, and citizens can frame the same event in dramatically different ways depending on what they emphasize, omit, or interpret. That doesn’t necessarily mean one side has complete control over the historical record—it often means multiple narratives are competing simultaneously.

One useful way to think about it is that there are several “layers” of history:

* Events: what physically happened.
* Records: documents, videos, testimony, data.
* Interpretation: what those events meant.
* Memory: what later generations choose to remember.

The first layer is fixed once it occurs. The latter three are continually contested and revised.

This is one reason why transparency, independent journalism, archival preservation, open records, and multiple eyewitness accounts are valuable. They make it harder for any single narrative—whether promoted by governments, media organizations, corporations, or political movements—to become the only surviving account.

In that sense, history isn’t simply written by the winner; it’s continually rewritten, challenged, and reconstructed by later readers working from whatever evidence survives.